THE LAST EASY NIGHT
A Chronicle of the Obsidian Lanterns

PART I: THE VOICE UNDER THE FLOOR
Dawn broke over Riften in grey harbor-light, gulls crying over the water. They cinched their packs, counted their coin twice, and loaded everything into the cart while Bjorn checked the wheel-pins the way he always did — twice. Mable stamped her feet in the traces, impatient to be moving. Beside her Balthazzar, the black mare, stood perfectly still, already watching the road ahead.

Klimmek crossed over while they were still finishing up and walked straight to Bjorn. He'd brought no speech, and he spoke without one. Three days he'd told that room the same thing, he said, and half of them just wanted him to shut up and drink. He was grinning now. And then Bjorn had gone and put together six of the best Skyrim had, and he'd just — gone.

He turned to the rest of them before Bjorn could answer. All of you. His voice caught on it, and he waved the rest off with a short laugh, scrubbing a hand across his face.

Bjorn took the offered hand in both of his instead of shaking it. He was grinning too. You kept an old man sane the last three days, lad. He pulled Klimmek into one hard, quick embrace, clapped him twice on the back, and stepped away. Go on. Get that ale finished before it goes flat.

The gates swung open. They went. Looking back once, Klimmek was still standing there, one hand raised.

The road took them north into hills gone gold with the turn of the season. The light was thin and clean. The wheels found their rhythm, and mile by mile an old feeling settled over all of them: ease. Full packs. Paid coin. Warm bread from Riften's ovens, still soft in the saddlebags. A road that asked only that they follow it.

Mable plodded on. Balthazzar walked beside her, head high, ears forward, reading the hills the whole way.

Then, from under the cart's floorboards — muffled by canvas and the false bottom — a dry old voice said, with enormous dignity: "...Are we far enough now? My legs fell asleep a day ago."

Nobody had thought about him since Riften. He had ridden two days folded into the dark beneath their feet, and somewhere in the long unspooling of everything since — the horse, the farewells, the leaving — the old man they had smuggled out under the city's nose had slipped clean out of the company's mind, the way the thing set down most carefully in a crisis is the first thing forgotten once the crisis breaks.

So when the voice came up out of the floor, no one placed it. Ismara's hand was already moving before the sentence finished — an Atmoran ice glaive building itself out of nothing in her grip, cold and total and instant — and by the time the boards lifted and a grey head rose blinking into the daylight, the blade was already laid against his throat.

He did not flinch from it. A spear of ice at his windpipe, two days of dark behind him, and the first thing he did was take offense.

"Two days." He ignored the blade the way a lecturer ignores a raised hand. "Two days I have lain under that floor, and not one of you thought to look. Do you understand what could have been down there in my place? A Thalmor plant. A garrotte. A corpse gone ripe enough to walk you all onto a gibbet the moment a gate-guard leaned in for a sniff—"

There was only one man in Skyrim who would deliver a seminar on tradecraft from the wrong end of a knife, and the seminar was how they knew him. Esbern. The old Blade off the Steps, hauled halfway across the province in a cart and left to season under the floorboards.

Esbern pushed the ice aside with the back of one hand and went right on. "I have survived thirty years by checking. Every door. Every floor. Every cart." He straightened his coat, and his voice, and fixed them each in turn. "If no one in this company is checking, I will be dead of inattention long before a dragon ever gets the chance." A beat. "So. Who is checking the cart from now on?"

Nobody argued the point. It fell to Ismara — the same hand that had held the blade to his throat now the one that would count him each morning, and no one commented on the symmetry aloud, though several of them noticed it.

He shoved the ice-blade's memory away with the same economy he shoved everything: no grudge carried forward, no grievance nursed. He straightened his coat, took stock of the road, the hills, the season, and set to the work he'd come for.

PART II: THE MAP
He unrolled it on the cart bed that afternoon, and the company gathered round — pins and charcoal and twine strung taut between them, thirty years of one man's watching laid flat on a board built for exactly this.

Red twine first. Five priests, he said, asleep under five mountains until they weren't, and he walked two fingers down the row of pins. The loose one — Rahgot's — hung off its tomb by a single strand, and it drew his longest look. That one had woken on its own and walked out, the tomb left empty behind him, no mark on it, as though he'd merely stood and gone. The other four Esbern couldn't place yet. That was what the Dragonstone would give him. Without it, he was guessing at graves.

Then the grey. His hand crossed to the other half of the board and his voice roughened with it — four pins here, the Eldergleam, the Steps, the Throat, Darkwater Crossing, each ringed twice in charcoal. This was not the Dragon Cult. He'd checked it against every pattern he held for them, and none of it sat. He stared at the blank middle of those four circles, where a name belonged and none would come. He didn't know who was doing this. He didn't know what they wanted. He knew only that it wasn't the priests, and that the ground stayed dead behind them.

It was Saijah who lit it. She'd been giving him what she carried all through — her own read on the sickness in the ground — and somewhere in it the shape came clear to him faster than his prepared telling would have reached it. Two ends of the world, he said slowly, finding it as he said it. Two hands at work. One of them a war. One of them something worse, for having no war in it.

The war was Alduin. The World-Eater — he ends the age, and the next one turns up behind him, and a thing with a will can be faced and fought and killed by someone strong enough to reach it. The other he would not call a war. It wanted nothing he could put a name to. It only left the land dead where it passed.

And when Saijah gave him the rest of what she carried of the cult — Dagon's people, what they believed, what they reached for — his hand came flat to rest on the grey twine, and something in his face went hard and old. This was the thing he'd tracked for weeks and never once been able to name. Mythic Dawn. Two hundred years gone, and he'd thought the order dead with them. Daedra-worshippers, Dagon's own, certain past all reasoning that the Divines were jailers and their lord the one who would break the lock. They had murdered an Emperor and his three sons for it — the line spent, the Dragonfires gone dark for want of an heir to light them, Oblivion pouring through the gap the dead had left, until another Emperor spent himself into a god to close it again. No one had to put a crimson robe in front of him or a scratched sigil. Her account met his four circles, and the name simply arrived, and he did not look glad to be right.

The Throat, he told them then, was no mere holy mountain. It was a pillar — one of the stones that held the floor of the world up off the dark beneath it — and cracked, it let time itself come loose in the cellar of things. Saijah's own skull had been telling her that much the length of the road south; he only gave the ache its name.

When they told him where they were bound — Ivarstead, the mountain, the grey-robed monks at the head of the Steps — he did not reach for their reins. He'd already gathered, from the way Saijah built toward it, that Bleak Falls came after. He sat back with what little surprise he had left to spend, and let them go. The monastery sat on neither thread. That was a later story, for the day a Dragonborn finally stood up and needed the Voice. Go, he said. He would mind the pins.

The one thing he pressed, the one thing he would always press, was the stone. Bleak Falls Barrow, and the Dragonstone in it — a map of every dragon grave in Skyrim, lying in a ruin no one troubled to watch. Everything they did before they held it was a flinch and not a plan. He didn't force the point. He set it in front of them once more, the way he'd set it a hundred times again, and let the cart carry them on.

Rahgot he already half-held — a few words caught up through the floorboards on the ride out, the sixth mask and the five beneath it and the line about the faithful made one, enough to file without dragging the telling from anyone. He turned the old anomaly over one more time and set it back unfinished: priests remembered for their fury, and moving since they woke with a patience that fury has never had. He set it among everything else he could not yet close, and waited on it, the way he waited on all of it, for the world to hand him the next piece.

PART III: THE GOLDEN WOOD
The road bent around a stand of gold-leaved aspens at dusk, and the light ahead of them wasn't dusk-light at all — it was lantern-light, warm and low, spilling out of eight patched tents pitched in a rough ring off the verge. A cookfire burned at the center. Rugs were laid between the tents with goods on them: stoppered bottles in rows, dried herbs hanging from the tentpoles, blades with a deep southern curve forged somewhere the trade roads ran warmer than Skyrim ever did.

A Khajiit in a coat of a hundred patches spotted the cart and came across the firelight fast, already talking, already sizing them up. Travelers — and with horses under them, and a cart behind! Ahkari had been waiting all day for someone worth the good prices. Sit, sit, look, touch, everything here was friendlier than it looked. Tea while they decided? The tea came free. It was the buying after that Ahkari was good at.

The tea was saffron and lavender, and it went over well enough that half the company was still holding a cup an hour later. The haggling that followed was social, unhurried, the kind of trade that happens because two parties enjoy trading, not because either one needs to win. Saijah walked away with the exotic hunting bow, the one strung with something that wasn't gut — Envenomed, Ahkari called it, and wouldn't say what the string actually was. Orion tried to unload a set of Dwemer centurion eyes he'd been carrying since the ruins, crystal and cold in his palm, and found no buyer for them; he kept them. And Ismara, working through Ahkari's stock with the patient thoroughness of a woman who read everything twice, came away with the Imga Longblade — a two-handed curved sword out of Elsweyr's deep forests, great-ape-forged, artifact-adjacent — along with lavender, a handful of alocasia fruit, and a Sun's Dust potion tucked into her bag for later.

Esbern crossed to the curved blades on his own, unprompted, and turned one over in his hands. The caravan didn't carry the Blades' own Akaviri steel, but he found himself interested anyway, quietly, the way a scholar recognizes a cousin discipline even in an unfamiliar hand. Not our old style, he said. But whoever ground this edge understood the same thing we did. It wasn't a purchase. It wasn't a lead. It was just an old man, for a moment, admiring craft.

Ahkari traded the way she always traded — a rumor offered, then a real question following it, watching what came back before she offered the next one. She heard, in pieces, over the course of the evening: a grim swordsman and a coughing priestess who'd walked into a sealed, plague-rotten Windhelm when everyone sane was walking out; a hunter east of here swearing he'd seen two dragons, real ones, wheeling low and heading for the Rift. And, once, when she asked after the sword one of them carried without ever asking outright, she looked away fast, on purpose, and let the silence be the whole of her answer. Some things she was happier not knowing.

PART IV: THE STORY AT THE FIRE
Ahkari settled onto the crate by the fire, and the caravan children came first — they always came first — filling in the ground closest to her knees. She waited until the smallest one was settled. Then she began, and her voice was not the market voice. It was older and slower, and it carried.

In the Rift, south and east of here, there was a wood called Thornheart, and its heart was alive that very night. A sickness had gotten into it once, she told them — down into the roots, up into the heart-tree, a body made of stolen things: bark for skin, old bone through it like veins, two wolves of thorn and shadow sleeping at its feet. It had taken three woodcutters. Then a priestess of Kynareth who'd come to heal the trees, and it held all four of them alive inside its trunk, feeding on them the way the sick thing feeds on the well.

Five heroes went in after them. The wood didn't want them there — it moved its paths behind their backs, closed the way out, unmade the way forward — but they learned its trick, read it the way hunters read a trail, and it brought them, tired and bleeding, to the heart.

The heart-thing met them and shrugged off their finest blows. Fire broke on its bark like water. Arrows turned on the bone. The ground split, and the wolves came up, and the fight was everywhere at once. The orc among them saw what the others couldn't spare eyes for — the faces still living in the trunk — and cut the first woodcutter free while his companions held the line. Then the second. And when he raised his blade to the third, the priestess, she found breath enough to beg him: wait. Careful. With the beast roaring at his back and death one heartbeat behind him, he slowed his hands anyway, and cut her free gently, like a mother untangling a child's hair.

The beast knew what it had lost, and grew with its rage — taller, thicker, mindless — and brought one arm down like a felled tree on the only thing standing between it and the priestess he'd just freed. He'd had room to run. He stood instead. One blow, one sound like an anvil struck once, and he was gone.

She didn't run either, weak as she was — she raised a ward over the strangers who'd come for her and spent what little she had left healing them. And out of the maze at last came the fifth, a wizard the wood had swallowed the whole fight, who broke through the treeline with fire in both hands.

Then came the small one.

A Khajiit, Ahkari told the children, like this one, like you, like your mothers and your fathers. No greatsword. No siege-magic. Two hands wrapped in old fighter's leather, and every gift the moons ever braided into their people. He went up — over the wolves, over the fire — and came down spinning, and cut that monster clean in half. And Riften — stone walls, shut gates, guards who asked their kind to wait outside in the cold — opened its gate for him. He walked through the front of it, in daylight, welcomed, while the whole market watched.

She had no way to know, telling it, exactly who sat across her fire. But partway through, someone in the company said the name plainly — the Lanterns, that's who we are — and Ahkari's eyes found them across the flames at the exact moment she said it in the telling too, and held there a beat longer than the story strictly needed. She knew, then, or near enough. The strongest Khajiit among them, she said, looking nowhere else. And somewhere behind her, unnoticed by the children, Ismara had been shaping small shadow-puppets out of ice the whole telling — a grove, a beast, a spinning blade — throwing their shapes against the tent canvas in time with the words, so the story had pictures as well as a voice.

When it ended, the caravan children didn't go straight to sleep. They went to play, the way children do after a good story — reenacting the whole battle at the edge of the firelight, underfoot and loud, half a game nobody outside it could explain. Mila watched with the careful hunger of a girl who'd never once been allowed to join something like that. Saijah caught it, crossed over, said something quiet, and sent her in.

Mila chose to be Saijah. Ismara built her a small ice wolf to ride, and the girl went tearing around the firelight on its back, drawing an invisible bow at invisible monsters, and for the length of one evening the company that had killed the thing in the story watched a child play at being them.

PART V: THE FIRE BURNS DOWN
The evening scattered the way evenings do, everyone finding their own corner of it.

Saijah and Varon found their way to it first — or she found her way to him, crossing to where he sat and dropping down beside him. It was Saijah who put the question out, blunt the way she put everything: did he like her, or something near enough. He said yes. He did. She took it in and made no show of knowing what to do with it. She knew what she needed, though, and she said that plainly too — that she had to be able to depend on him. That he couldn't run off again, the way he had before. That she needed him there.

He said okay.

Later, still turning over what Saijah had asked of him, Varon went looking for Orion — the steadiest hand in the company, and the one he'd quietly settled on as worth the asking. He wanted to know how a man made himself into the thing Saijah had said she needed: someone she could depend on, someone who would not run. He was all the way in on her, and he had come to learn how to be worth it.

Orion took the question with the gravity of a man who had long ago settled it for himself. "You hold your position," he said. "You don't retreat when it gets hard. That's the whole of it." He said it like a rule proven across a hundred fights and never once broken.

It was not, on examination, an answer. It was the same thing Saijah had already told Varon herself, dressed now in a soldier's language, and it left him no further along than he'd started. Before he let the matter go, Varon told Orion the Honorhall work had been clean — controlled, exact, the mark of a man who knew his business. Orion accepted this the way he accepted most things offered to him, gladly, and did not appear to notice he'd given nothing back for it.

What mattered to Varon was that he had asked at all.

Down at the alchemy bench, Nora was working the same question from the other side of it. She'd gone looking for Saijah first — Alfonso rode with Orion this leg, and she wanted to study him, to learn whether a soul anchored in iron could be copied rather than moved, and she wouldn't so much as float the rapier without Orion's yes behind it, not after what the iron had already nearly cost her. The looking took her to where Saijah actually was: down with Ismara and Ylva, GEAR turning slow at the center of them like a mill-wheel, grinding the components of Sun's Dust apart for study. They all ended up working it together, and somewhere in the patient turn of the thing, Nora asked Saijah the question she couldn't put to anyone nearer it. How do you know, with someone.

Saijah gave her whatever she gave her — that part was theirs.

Off past the firelight, Mila couldn't sleep. She was up on the cart with a blanket around her shoulders, going to no one, only sitting where she'd be seen the way she always sat. Saijah went to hand her off to Bjorn for the night, meaning to give the old man the child and the evening both and take her back only if she had to.

She had to. They found him out past the light with Mable and Balthazzar, sitting in the dirt, thoroughly and uselessly drunk — a war-hound with a dragon's fire still lodged behind his eyes and no other door to put it through. He didn't see them coming. Saijah didn't wake him. She turned around with Mila's hand in hers and walked the girl back to the fire, and the two of them sat there together until the child's eyes went heavy and closed. Ismara had bought her a stuffed rabbit and a small wooden sword at the tents earlier, for reasons she gave no one, and Mila slept holding both.

And late, when the fire had burned to coals, Nora crossed to Orion and stopped circling it.

She sat close, on purpose, near enough that they were almost touching, and for a while she said nothing, only watched the coals with him. Then:

"I've been asking everyone all night how you're supposed to know," she said finally. "I don't think there's an answer. I think you just have to say the thing and find out."

She didn't get the rest of it out. Orion closed the distance before she could, and the company that saw it — most of them did — broke into cheering, loud and unashamed and long. What came after belonged to the two of them and the dark of her tent, and the camp let them have it.

PART VI: THE SMOKE
It was at the tents, hours earlier, that Saijah had first tried what the caravan sold quieter than the rest — moon sugar first, sold openly, a normal caravan good; then skooma, a step removed from the open stall, the way Ahkari kept it.

The moon sugar gave her a clean, humming energy that lasted the better part of an hour and faded without a mark. The skooma was different. It opened something in her that felt, for a long borderless stretch she never found the edges of, like a well with no bottom — magic answering her call without cost, without the familiar drag of her own reserves running dry. When it let her go, the crash underneath it was worse than the height had been good, and something in her had already decided, before the rest of her caught up to the decision, that she wanted to feel that particular bottomless thing again.

She bought three more bottles before the caravan packed up its rugs for the night.

Nobody at the fire noticed, not with everything else the evening was carrying. It sat in her pack the way the black mare's twelve thousand septims had sat in Bjorn's want — quiet, unspoken, and already costing something none of them could see yet.

PART VII: MORNING
The company slept, in whatever configuration the night had left them in, and woke to a caravan already half broken down around them — tents coming off their frames, pack-animals loaded, Ahkari moving through it all shouting good-natured instructions at her own people in a language that wasn't quite Cyrodilic and wasn't quite anything else either.

They said their goodbyes, packed the cart, and took the road north again, into the open stretch that would carry them toward whatever waited in the sky above the logging cuts ahead.

Behind them the caravan was already breaking down, rugs rolled and fires kicked cold, its people bound for the next circle and the next audience for the Thornheart story. An old warrior slept off his grief in the frost with two horses standing guard over him. A child slept with a rabbit in one arm and a wooden sword in the other. A mage and a swordsman had finally stopped circling the thing between them. And folded into Saijah's pack, down where no one had thought to look, rode three bottles of the one thing that had answered when nothing else would.

They rode into the good weather sure of the thing they were always sure of — that the danger, when it came, would come from the road ahead.

— End of The Last Easy Night —


